  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for the minimum number of set bits in the binary representation of 2023*n. This is equivalent to finding the minimum Hamming weight of a multiple of 2023. Since 2023 is odd, we can use properties of modular arithmetic and the fact that any number with Hamming weight 1 is a power of 2. The problem reduces to finding the smallest Hamming weight k such that there exists a sum of k powers of 2 that is divisible by 2023.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "Analyze the number 2023. Determine its prime factorization. Check if 2023 is coprime to 2. Verify if there exist powers of 2 that are congruent to 1 modulo 2023 using Euler's Totient Theorem or by checking the order of 2 modulo 2023. This will help determine if k(n)=1 is possible."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_2",
      "instructions": "Investigate the possibility of k(n) = 2. This requires finding if there exist integers a and b such that (2^a + 2^b) is divisible by 2023. This is equivalent to checking if 2^(a-b) is congruent to -1 modulo 2023 (assuming a > b). Test small values or use the properties of the order of 2 modulo the factors of 2023 to prove or disprove this."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_3",
      "instructions": "Investigate the possibility of k(n) = 3. This requires finding if there exist integers a, b, and c such that (2^a + 2^b + 2^c) is divisible by 2023. This is equivalent to checking if 2^x + 2^y + 1 is congruent to 0 modulo 2023 for some x, y. Systematically check if such a combination exists by examining the residues of powers of 2 modulo 2023."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent will combine the results by checking the feasibility of k(n) = 1, then k(n) = 2, then k(n) = 3, and so on. The first k for which a solution is found (or proven to exist) is the minimum k(n). The helpers provide the rigorous proofs for the impossibility or existence of these small Hamming weights."
}

